<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="inv-5-8">
  <title>Investigation 5.8: Height and Foot Size</title>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises5-8" hidden-label="yes">
    <title>The Study</title>

    <p>This investigation uses student height and foot-length data to build least-squares regression ideas from prediction error.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-a" label="I5.8.a"><title>Identify Variables</title><statement><p>(a) Identify observational units, explanatory variable, and response variable.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-b" label="I5.8.b"><title>Baseline Prediction</title><statement><p>(b) Predict height from the sample of heights alone with one number.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-c" label="I5.8.c"><title>Prediction Error</title><statement><p>(c) Would that prediction always be correct?</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Definition: Residual</title>
      <p>Residual for observation <m>i</m> is <m>y_i-\hat{y}_i</m>.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-d" label="I5.8.d"><title>Compute Residuals</title><statement><p>(d) Complete residual table and compare overestimation vs underestimation counts.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-e" label="I5.8.e"><title>Sign of Residual</title><statement><p>(e) Interpret positive and negative residuals.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-f" label="I5.8.f"><title>Overall Error Metric</title><statement><p>(f) Suggest a way to combine residuals to quantify overall error.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-g" label="I5.8.g"><title>Why Sum of Residuals Fails</title><statement><p>(g) Compute sum of residuals and explain why it is not useful for fit quality.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-h" label="I5.8.h"><title>Proof Sum Residuals from Mean</title><statement><p>(h) Show mathematically that residuals from the sample mean sum to zero.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-i" label="I5.8.i"><title>Alternative Criteria</title><statement><p>(i) Suggest two alternatives that avoid cancellation.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-j" label="I5.8.j"><title>Calculus Minimization</title><statement><p>(j) Use calculus to show minimizing sum of squared errors over a constant predictor yields the sample mean.</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Predicting Height from Foot Length</title>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-k" label="I5.8.k"><title>Describe Scatterplot</title><statement><p>(k) Describe association between height and foot length.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-l" label="I5.8.l"><title>Movable Line</title><statement><p>(l) Use applet movable line and record your best-fit equation.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-m" label="I5.8.m"><title>Compare Class Lines</title><statement><p>(m) Did everyone get the same equation?</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-n" label="I5.8.n"><title>Best-Line Criterion</title><statement><p>(n) Propose a criterion for deciding which line is best.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-o" label="I5.8.o"><title>Absolute Error Criterion</title><statement><p>(o) Compute SAE for your line and compare across class.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-p" label="I5.8.p"><title>Squared Error Criterion</title><statement><p>(p) Compute SSE for your line and compare.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-q" label="I5.8.q"><title>Improve Line for SSE</title><statement><p>(q) Adjust line to minimize SSE and report equation.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-r" label="I5.8.r"><title>Least Squares Line</title><statement><p>(r) Use applet regression line and compare with your line.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    </paragraphs>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Definition: Least Squares Regression Line</title>
      <p>The least squares line minimizes SSE among all lines.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-s" label="I5.8.s"><title>How to Determine Coefficients</title><statement><p>(s) Suggest a technique to determine slope and intercept from data.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-t" label="I5.8.t"><title>Derivatives for SSE</title><statement><p>(t) Differentiate SSE with respect to intercept and slope.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-u" label="I5.8.u"><title>Solve Normal Equations</title><statement><p>(u) Solve for least-squares coefficients.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-v" label="I5.8.v"><title>Compute Coefficients from Summaries</title><statement><p>(v) Use summary statistics and <m>b_1=r s_y/s_x</m>, <m>b_0=\bar{y}-b_1\bar{x}</m>.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-w" label="I5.8.w"><title>Predictions and Slope Meaning</title><statement><p>(w) Predict heights at two nearby foot lengths and relate difference to slope.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-x" label="I5.8.x"><title>Interpret Slope</title><statement><p>(x) Interpret slope in context.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-y" label="I5.8.y"><title>Interpret Intercept</title><statement><p>(y) Interpret intercept and discuss meaningfulness.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-z" label="I5.8.z"><title>Extrapolation</title><statement><p>(z) Predict at far-out x and explain why this is less reliable.</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Definition: Extrapolation</title>
      <p>Extrapolation is prediction outside observed x-range and is usually ill-advised.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-aa" label="I5.8.aa"><title>SSE from Mean Line</title><statement><p>(aa) Compute SSE when predicting with <m>\bar{y}</m> only.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-bb" label="I5.8.bb"><title>Coefficient of Determination</title><statement><p>(bb) Compute percentage SSE reduction from mean line to regression line and interpret as <m>R^2</m>.</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Definition: Coefficient of Determination</title>
      <p><m>R^2</m> is the proportion of response variability explained by regression on the explanatory variable.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-cc" label="I5.8.cc"><title>Residual Standard Deviation</title><statement><p>(cc) Compute and interpret <m>s=\sqrt{SSE/(n-2)}</m>.</p></statement><response/></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Study Conclusions</title>
      <p>Height and foot length show a moderately strong positive linear association; least-squares regression improves prediction over using the mean alone but still leaves unexplained variability.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-8-practice" label="I5.8.practice"><title>Practice Problem 5.8</title><statement><p>For Cat Jumping data: compute and interpret <m>r</m>, <m>r^2</m>, slope, intercept, and <m>s</m>.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>
